    en: `Creatine [cite: 1]
Its Importance [cite: 2]
For the Average Person [cite: 3]
- Improving Daily Energy: Creatine helps the body produce extra energy in situations that require sudden effort, like running or lifting heavy objects[cite: 4]. This makes the average person feel more capable of facing daily life challenges[cite: 5].
Brain Functions: The brain uses the same energy system (ATP) as muscles, and creatine helps recharge it[cite: 6]. This can improve short-term memory, reaction speed, and attention, which is very important for students or people whose work requires high concentration[cite: 7].
Elderly (without kidney problems): Creatine is of particular importance for healthy older adults[cite: 8]. With advancing age, muscle mass and physical strength naturally decrease, which increases the risk of falling or losing independence[cite: 9]. Creatine helps them maintain muscles, reduces strength weakness, and improves daily mobility[cite: 10]. Also, some studies have shown that it may support mental functions and reduce age-related cognitive decline[cite: 11].
- Medical Conditions: In some neurological diseases like Parkinson's or Multiple Sclerosis, creatine is being studied as an auxiliary agent to improve cellular energy, which may help in reducing fatigue and improving quality of life[cite: 12].
For Athletes and Bodybuilders [cite: 13]
- Increasing Strength and Explosiveness: Creatine enables the athlete to lift heavier weights or perform more repetitions, which translates directly to faster training progress[cite: 14].
- Improving Performance: In high-intensity exercises like sprinting, jumping, or weightlifting, because it increases the muscle's ability to produce rapid energy[cite: 15].
Increasing Muscle Mass: Not directly, but because it allows for stronger and more frequent workouts, the natural result is faster and more visible muscle growth[cite: 16].
Recovery: Some studies say it may reduce muscle damage after exercise and help in faster recovery, which allows the athlete to return to training more quickly[cite: 17].
- Volumization: Creatine attracts water inside the muscle cells, making the muscle look fuller and creating a suitable environment for muscle building[cite: 18].
What is Creatine? [cite: 19]
Creatine is a natural compound formed in the body from amino acids (Arginine, Glycine, Methionine)[cite: 20]. It is primarily stored in the muscles as "phosphocreatine", which is considered a rapid energy reserve that the body uses during sudden movements or high-intensity exercises[cite: 21]. The body naturally synthesizes a portion of it in the liver, kidneys, and pancreas, but we can also get it from food (like red meat and fish)[cite: 22].
Why must we take it as a dietary supplement? [cite: 23]
Although creatine is present in food, the amount we get from a natural diet is often insufficient to achieve optimal benefits[cite: 24]. To reach the levels that noticeably support athletic performance or even mental functions, we must take it as a dietary supplement[cite: 25]. Athletes, especially, need higher doses than they can get from food, and supplements provide a concentrated, easily absorbed dose, ensuring that the body has a sufficient reserve to support muscular and mental performance[cite: 26].
How it works inside the body [cite: 27]
Creatine acts as an "extra battery" for the muscles[cite: 28]. When the muscle needs rapid energy, it uses ATP (Adenosine Triphosphate) molecules[cite: 28]. The problem is that the ATP reserve is very small and runs out quickly (in a few seconds)[cite: 29]. Here comes the role of creatine: it recharges the ATP through a reaction with phosphate, and thus gives the muscle the ability to sustain high effort for a longer period[cite: 30]. In other words: Creatine does not build muscles directly, but it makes the muscle able to work more, lift heavier, and train at a higher intensity, which ultimately leads to greater muscle growth[cite: 31].
Important Notes [cite: 32]
- Creatine is one of the most scientifically researched supplements, and it is considered very safe when used correctly[cite: 33]. The common dose is about 3-5 grams daily[cite: 34].
- Some people may feel a slight weight gain due to water retention inside the muscles, which is normal and beneficial for the athlete[cite: 35]. One must drink enough water to avoid any digestive or kidney problems[cite: 36].`,
